Her mother had fallen off of a stepping stool while attempting to grab a vase from the highest cabinet they had.

This study was to show that adherence to a “Mediterranean Diet” (Med diet), as reflected by a high “alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score”, is associated with reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke and stroke mortality.  The aMed diet is a modified version of the Med diet and is characterized by higher consumption of plant foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes, but including fruits, nuts, whole grains and legumes), monounsaturated fat (compared to saturated fat) and fish, and lower consumption of animal products and saturated fats.  Moderate intake of alcohol is allowed.
  	

Prior prospective studies documented an inverse association between adherence to a Med diet and risk of total and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality and an intervention trial showed the Med diet to be more effective than a low-fat diet, in promoting weight loss and lowering the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese individuals.  Prior studies did not focus on stroke or stroke mortality.


This epidemiological study followed 74,886 women, 38 to 63 years of age, without a history of CVD or diabetes, who are participants in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study of 121,700 female nurses in 11 US states.  Six times, from 1984 to 2004, the authors computed an aMed diet score from self-reported “food frequency questionnaires” (“FFQs) designed to assess nutrient intake during the preceding year.  More than 95% of nurses continued participation throughout the 20 year period. FFQs were subjected to validation studies.  Reports of CHD, fatal CHD and stroke were confirmed by review of medical or hospital records, autopsy or death certificates. Where records were not available, cases were considered “probable” and included, with about 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts so classified. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status and use of postmenopausal hormone were calculated for each FFQ, and beginning in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was assessed. 

To reduce random variation for an individual and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging together scores from two prior years).  Adjustments were made for “confounders” (factors that could confuse results) by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to assess the association between an aMed score and risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types. 

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as reflected by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of incident CHD and stroke in women.  During 20 years of follow-up, 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (fatal CHD and strokes combined) were found. Women in the top aMed quintile were at lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared with those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In 2007, the United States of America fell into a crushing financial crisis. Unemployment increased, the housing market crashed, and many of America’s largest and most important corportations were left in ruin. This recession persists today, so we must ask the question: how did this crisis occur, and how can we stop it? In short, the financial crisis was created by selfish and naïve political decision-making that pressured banks and firms into issuing sub-prime loans into an already immature and unsufficient financial infrastructure. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwite and repackage these mortgages into CDO’s and CDS’. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks were short on capital reserve and transferred this chaos onto the repacked mortgages that they had sold, and on to the rest of the economy.
	The financial crisis had its roots in 1999 of the Clinton era, as the President was aiming for a second term in office. He sought to extend his presidential tenure by augmenting his popularity. To accomplish this the Clinton administration relaxed lending restrictions, which helped to set the grim stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later.  Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation's biggest underwriter of home mortgages, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and moderate income people and felt pressure from stock holders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits.” Holmes would go on to correctly foresee the consequences of these actions: “But the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As detailed in the introduction, and as Holmes foresaw, ill-advised lending would certainly lead to the meltdown of the economy.
	Many factors combined to throw the economy into tailspin, one of which was the new and complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDO’s) were all used extensively in the years leading up to the crisis, and only served to intertwine more sectors of the economy into the housing market. This led to U.S. households, and financial markets in general, to overleverage themselves in the housing market, leaving them extremely vulnerable to even small changes in price. 
	Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were spited. The top five U.S. investment banks all together reported $4.1 trillion dollars of mortgage debts in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the USA’s GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold exceptionally cheap, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subjected to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt, and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition.  That place in your story where you stretch your little writer's wings and take flight, astounding one and all with your magnetic, nay magical prose.  Or the part where your readers fall asleep and/or hit the "Back" button while cursing your name.  Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her monitor when she finds herself in the middle of Too Much Information, and not even in the fun way.

Exposition is not your friend.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still stumbles into long passages of text where nothing happens, or worse, too much.  Exposition is the little devil sitting on your shoulder that says to get the history out of the way to get to the good parts (not to be confused with the devil sitting on the other shoulder urging the author to tell her audience every single detail of the childhoods of each character).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple prose.  In film, the exposition happens when one character tells another a core-dump of information ala "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In fiction, the author's doing the telling.

An example is in order.  As you are reading a story, you are told that the heroine met her beloved at such a place and time, that they were married in a gala fashion, and that her husband was murdered in front of her eyes.  You would not expect this entire sequence to take two pages, during which time both he and she only get two lines of dialogue each.  You would expect the author to spend some time on the husband's character, evidencing by his speech and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you would equally expect the heroine to show through big and small ways how much his presence in her life changed and enriched her (especially if the story were to tell you flat out later that this was the case).  A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally involved with his fate and would give you insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts and beliefs and dreams as reflected through the prism of his eyes, and so on.  You would mourn his death with her, and so grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect meat on the simple bone of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that meat.  (*looks at metaphor, sighs, plunges onward*)  Sometimes it is tempting to rush past certain things.  Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, and he's the night manager of a gas station now, and he was married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on the weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two newscast’s from Columbus, Ohio. The first one that was “live” was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The lead story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio who had stabbed his wife, it did not state her name however his name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his mug shot and he looked like pure evil. They devoted only about two minutes to this story as it was developing. The only details they provide he had stabbed her multiple times and had been arrested. I think they spent an appropriate amount of time on this story. 
	The second story was about an early morning shooting of Travis Buyers, 18. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area and had been critically injured; there had been no arrests made at the time or any suspects. The SWAT Team was investigating the crime. This story seemed to be short, and I believe that might have been due to the fact this was a “black” man or a black neighborhood. I noticed (and have for years) that minorities are glossed over when they are a victim of a crime. If say a “white” child or adult is kidnapped or missing or a victim of a crime the media goes nuts; but if a minority person it’s lucky if it is even mentioned. 
	The next story was about the gunshot hole that had been found in the Med-Flight helicopter. Details were given about where they thought the incident happened. It had been determined that it was a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle that had hit the helicopter. Crime-Stoppers are offering a five-thousand dollar reward for tips that lead to the arrest of the shooter. 
	The next story was concerning the rain and thunderstorms predicted for Saturday afternoon. They said the temperatures would remain in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. The length of time was a little short, but they wanted to use it as a “teaser” so that you would stay tuned. 
	They also ran with a story about a robbery of a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. They said it was dark-skinned black man who robbed the store he was wearing a hoodie sweatshirt. They said he was about six-foot tall and weighed about one hundred and fifty pounds. I thought they devoted an unusual about of time emphasizing he was black and how dark he was. 
	Another story was about a Rene Rodriguez who was a convicted Texas Drug-Kingpin. He had been convicted of conspiring to distribute marijuana in large amounts to Ohio from Texas. One curious thing I noted, was instead of saying he was sentenced to twenty-five years in prison they said “300” months. I am not sure what the angle was there, whether they thought that sounded more harsh or what. They also mentioned he was a Hispanic man, I don’t believe that was really germane to the story.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within that bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, just to name a few. Brothers understand one another, far more than anyone else with that kind of bond, and they can only see themselves when looking at their brother. It is when a situation is at its most dire when the true nature of this bond shines through, be it good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry with them great a cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences that they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and see within that person their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the consequences of those actions is where their true character lies.  In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this theme, and all of the raging emotions that accompany it. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys set out on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life. The theme is expressed through direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator’s point of view, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which are heavy influences on his actions.
	The protagonist’s actions can all be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his little brother, Doodle, first go out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He had wanted a brother whom he could teach all of his worldly skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” He wanted a brother who could fill the role of “…someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn…” Obviously these things are impossible, given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making in unlikely he would even survive. Even then, it was nearly impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, his head filled with wild fantasies, to have all of those dreams crushed in an instant. In fact, he is even shown to bear some anger towards the small child, as he recalls beginning to contemplate killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? However, his heart melts when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist such hope! This shows that his conviction probably was not very strong. In the back of his mind, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complicated, creative information-processing system. As technology advanced from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also advanced. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you learn about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.
Information processing starts with input from the sensory organs, which transform physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing puts together very simple information such as color, orientation, and where the borders of the object are – where the color changes significantly over a short space – to decide that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at some steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing in this example might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.
Once information is processed to a degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even when spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.
In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to what the printed word looks like, phonemically, referring to what the word sounds like, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period of time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.
There are numerous models of how the knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on the way human subjects retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others based on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

Aldous Huxley criticizes the upcoming threat of both technology and the capitalistic structure by which it is reinforced through the creation of a dystopia in the novel Brave New World. Its people value community above the individual, and are conditioned from the very beginning to pursue immediate happiness above all else. The citizens are revealed to be pawns in a larger game, confined to one ideology as dictated by the World Controller. By examining the work under the lenses of Marxist theism, one notices the underlying suspicions of the author in regards to the development of aforementioned systems. Frequent terminology in Marxism, such as homogeny and reification, among others, reinforce the idea that Huxley’s novel is a commentary on the faults in the emerging economy from his time on.
Capitalism is satirized through the use of the Marxist thesis known as false consciousness. Essentially, the common citizenry is prevented from knowing true relations to other classes in economic terms, as they are primarily interested in their own gain. It is said to be the result of ideological control of the proletariat and common laborers, something quite obvious by the conditioning of the people in Brave New World. The common classes, Delta, Gamma, etc., have no true will of their own; through hypnopædia the drive to consume, to spend, to indulge is strengthened above all else.  This is manipulated, as previously stated, by the World Controller.  Hegemony, essentially the idea that groups of social classes are dominated by  a separate group of individuals in totality, is obviously used in this case. The lower classes are entirely unaware of the manipulation, quite literally ‘[buying]  into an ideology that supports that structure’ (i.e. capitalism & consumerism). ’ Upper classes are born with the ability to be aware of it but do nothing ; few Alphas or Betas beyond characters like Bernard do much more than likewise accept their place.  In fact, the  interactions of the social classes, as will be discussed  in greater length, are significant indications of the perceived oppression of capitalism.
Relationships between disparate individuals does not exist in Brave New World.  The novel seemingly refuses to distinguish the characters - they are, even  among major characters, lacking depth. Perhaps Huxley is suggesting that the rise of technology and capitalism together deprive man of their free will and expression. Love does not exist, nor do the extremes of any one emotion; rather, interactions are kept superficial, portrayed distinctly through  the males remarks  about women primarily about their physical appearance (i.e. pneumatic quality), and the females’  unashamed  comments about their encounters, so to speak.  Furthermore, each societal class’ complacency with their status in the hierarchy  indicate  the socioeconomic effect of capitalism.  Their absolute obedience of their part in the community is an indication of Marxist thought on the proletariat, who are falsely ensured of their own superiority over all else so long as they continue to consume, to obey, to stay in line with the rest of their peers.

I have been a student here at University Park for about two and a half years now, or four and a half semesters. For many, including myself, getting around on campus can be a problem. My freshman year I was placed in an East Halls dorm room; pretty much the furthest eastward limit of campus, not counting the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Traveling from my home in Stuart Hall to classes in such faraway places as Willard building, near the center of campus, could take up to 25 minutes by foot, especially if the weather was bad, as it often is in State College. Speaking to an alum not much older than myself, I learned that not long ago the East Halls dorms were set apart from the rest of the school by huge tracts of unused land. Today that empty space has been filled with sports fields, huge new buildings including the new Creamery and new health services building, and surrounded with apartments. As our campus continues to expand, getting from one place to another becomes more and more difficult. What is the best solution to the problem of mobility? On a college campus, it is the bicycle. But the bike by itself won't solve any problems. Students need to ride them, and the campus needs to be built to suit the needs of bicyclists.
	I was talking to a friend of mine who recently resumed bicycling after a several-year hiatus. He mentioned that he wondered why he ever stopped. “Bikes are great,” he said, “for a few years it wasn’t cool to ride a bike, but it’s the only way to get around.” In addition to being good for your body, bicycling is the most efficient way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and a little physical exertion will take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now live off campus; just as far from the center of campus as some dorms. The smartest decision I’ve made this year was to buy a bike. Every day, I have class in Thomas building, easily a twenty-five-minute walk from my home. Riding a bike can cut that time down to 5 minutes if I pedal fast enough. The only problem is, Pollock Road is the straightest shot to Thomas building from my house, and it's not always an easy road to travel on, bike or no bike. There are things to be said for walking as well, but personally I’m too busy to walk. If I didn’t have my bike, walking would be my only reliable option for getting to class. Walking to Thomas every day would take an extra 30-40 minutes out of my day. That’s over two and a half hours every week. Add to that all the other time I would have to spend walking to and from other classes, appointments, and etc. That’s more time than I can spare.

I want to study social work. I will work for Family and Children Services to help abused or neglected children and support troubled families. My values for social work are:
- Service
- Respect
- Ethical behavior
- Helping others improve relationships
- Improving myself professionally

I always wanted to help others but did not know what career to choose. In high school and college, I saw people hide from problems and use bad coping ways. I studied Psychology at Piedmont College. After graduating, I was still unsure about my career.

One day, a friend introduced me to a sixteen-year-old boy hiding from his abusive parents. I visited his parents and talked to the police. They asked me to talk to the parents. The parents blamed their son for his problems. This made me think about a career in social work.

Social justice is important in social work. Society says individuals are important, but often we try to be like everyone else. I am unique and do not like limits. In high school and college, I protested against social injustice: coloring my hair, wearing unique clothes, piercing ears, joining GSBA, fighting racism and discrimination. I will continue to protest.

This paper talks about two models, Biological and Sociocultural, and how they explain sleep problems, like insomnia. The Biological model looks at how genes and health work. The Sociocultural model looks at how people's lives and surroundings affect sleep. We will talk about these models and some research about insomnia.

There are different types of sleep problems. Some are Primary disorders, like Dyssomnias or Parasomnias. Others are with other health issues or medicines. Dyssomnias are problems with starting or staying asleep. Parasomnias are problems with unusual things happening while sleeping. We will mainly talk about insomnia.

The Biological model of sleep problems focuses on genes and how the body's sleep system works. Neurons in the brain control sleep and wakefulness. The study with mice showed that certain parts of these neurons help with sleep. If these parts do not work well, people may not sleep enough. This means there is a genetic part to sleep problems. If the problem is in the genes, it can affect many parts of life, like school and work.

This paper has three parts. First, it gives a short definition of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). Next, it explains how to diagnose CAPD, including common signs or "red flags". Finally, it gives ways teachers can help a student with CAPD in a regular classroom.

CAPD is when the brain does not process sound correctly. People with CAPD can hear normally, but the brain has trouble hearing and understanding sounds. This happens because the part of the brain that translates sound into words and separates speech from background noise does not work well.

The first mention of CAPD was in the 1950s, called "auditory imperception". Italian researchers started testing for it in 1954. A man named Kimura introduced a model to explain how it works in 1961. In 1977, a conference about CAPD was held, which led to more research on the disorder.

CAPD has many signs. A person may not know where a sound comes from or have trouble hearing two sounds at once. They may struggle to recognize sound patterns or understand changes in speech. They may not be able to follow the order of sounds. There are no known causes or one test for CAPD.

To diagnose CAPD, a patient is observed and tested on how they respond to sounds. There is no single test that works perfectly. Tests often give patients multiple sounds at once and ask them to pick out specific ones. Advanced tests record sounds in the ear and measure the brain's response.

The play Twelfth Night says that using a disguise can be useful for tricks, but in the end, a person must give up the disguise. A big problem is that this can cause someone to feel alone. So, a person must decide: keep their own identity or keep their relationships. Some people will be fine, but others will be upset. The topic of disguise and gender is difficult. Why does someone feel the need to change their identity? In Viola's case, it is to protect herself. She feels she must pretend to be a man in a new land. This plan works, but she does not fit in with other women. Olivia is confused and falls in love with her. She also has to deal with feelings for Orsino. The play may show that deception can help people face hidden emotions. For example, Olivia might have feelings for women. But, Olivia's feelings for Cesario change quickly, and she sees Cesario as family, not a love interest.

German colonial rule was brutal. Many people saw it as cruel, especially because of the genocide in South West Africa. German colonies had different rules and school systems. In East Africa, the British found many educated Africans. But in South West Africa, education was mostly done by missionaries with little help from the government. The government did help with European schools. This made big differences in education after German rule. This paper talks about why this happened. It looks at new research about settlers' and authorities' feelings towards Africans. Many books about German schools are in German. Cohen's study compares schools in South West Africa and East Africa. South West Africa had fewer settlers and more desert.

The music called Pop Music has many names. It has many types and small types. It is hard to count them all. It started 100 years ago. Many types have even smaller types. One type is called Heavy Metal. It is very different. It has many feelings and stories. It is also very loud and has a lot of music. It started with other music. Many people like it. It is like a big movement. It has many rules. Some people use drugs to make it. Many people like the dark part. It is different from other music. It has many stories about feelings. It is like a big family.

Many years before Surrealist artists started painting, Henri Rousseau was creating his own dreamlike scenes. His painting "The Dream," from 1910, shows a woman in a dream. It also shows Rousseau's own dreams and goals. He dreamed of being accepted and praised by other artists. He faced a choice: follow popular styles or stay unique. "The Dream" shows his struggle.

To understand "The Dream," know about Rousseau's life. He was born in France in 1844. His father was a tinsmith. Rousseau had no art training. He worked for France until he was forty. He was a gabelou, a customs inspector. His first wife and many children died. He painted to find comfort. He was a folk painter, not a romantic painter. He wanted to be accepted by the art world. He started painting when others were successful. He felt left behind. In "Modern French Painters," Jan Gordon says Matisse was different. Matisse feared painting simply. Rousseau wanted to paint conventionally to be accepted.

Many great thinkers have said that ethics and aesthetics are connected. They believe this because of a deep reason. John Keats wrote, "Beauty is truth, truth beauty — that is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." We learn many things in life through education or experience. But we also appreciate ethics and beauty without being taught about them. Both ethics and beauty try to describe, not prescribe. Our studies of morality and art aim to explain why something is beautiful or moral, not to create rules. No criticism can fully describe what is good or beautiful. People often say, "There's just something about it" when describing their favorite art or literature. Both art and ethics cannot be fully explained. Flannery O'Connor said, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way." Ethics and art have a similar power. They affect us deeply, but we cannot fully explain why.

Morality and art are closely related because we feel them deeply. This is true, especially with literature. Literature has a moral quality like no other art. It seems that moral standards are important to literature, like they are to life itself. Literature is important because it has values.

Today, Germany is a strong country. It has a unique culture from the Alps in München to the Baltic Sea city of Kiel. This culture can be felt from Köln on the Rhine River to Dresden on the Elbe River. This culture comes from many tribes.

Germania is the old land of the Germans. The name's origin is unclear. Some say it comes from a Germanic tribe called Tungrians. Tacitus, a Roman historian, said this tribe was known as Germans before crossing the Rhine to fight the Gauls. Others say it comes from the German word for spear (ger) or the Irish word for "to shout" (garim).

An early Roman historian, Tacitus, wrote about the Germans in AD 98. He said they were from Asia or Africa and came to Germany by ship. He said: "Who would leave Asia or Africa for Italy or Germany? Certainly not the Romans. They would only go for goods or to fight."

When Germanic tribes appeared in the first century, they lived on the border of the Roman Empire. They traded goods and skills with the Romans. They also served in the Roman army.

I looked at a toilet bowl. My mind was empty. I saw the brown mess. I did not feel much. I studied the picture in front of me. I thought about it. I did not understand. I had a book. It told me how to draw. I could not draw before. I tried to use the book's method. I put a square frame around the picture. I saw the toilet. I felt good. I wanted to draw. I touched the brush. My hand moved. I tried to move the brown mess. It did not move. I tried again. I tried to clean. I used a mop. I was angry. I tried to clean again. I liked the water. I felt calm. I cleaned again. I cleaned until the bowl was clean. I stood up. I was happy. I helped. I cleaned the toilet.

Teenagers are dying behind the wheel. Many problems cause this. The National Institutes of Health say the teen brain is not ready for driving. Teens lack experience. This causes more accidents. They also crash more when they drive with friends. A study shows this.
States try to make teens safer. They give temporary driver's licenses. These licenses limit how long teens can drive and when they can have other teens in the car. But these laws are not enough. Teens are not ready to drive safely. Dr. Marvin Zuckerman says 18 is too young for a regular driver's license.
By 2010, many more teens will be able to drive. This could cause more accidents. We need better laws.
Schools could teach future drivers, but no one under 18 could drive. A provisional permit could be issued before a full license. More driving hours with a teacher could be required. This could be based on the number of hours required by most states.
This law would protect teens. It would be similar to other laws in states. It could stop many accidents.

I looked at many old Edison films in the Library of Congress. Most of them were made between 1895 and 1901. Most of these films were called trick films. There were fifteen of them. These films use editing to make things look like magic or tricks. I studied many of these films. I looked at how they are made. I also looked at special films that are different. Most of these films are set in a stage. The camera does not move. It shows long and medium shots. It does not use close-up shots. This is like old theatre and vaudeville shows. The actors move side-to-side, but they do not walk towards or away from the camera. In one film, Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel, the actors move from one side of the stage to the other. The camera does not follow them. The shots in these films are usually long. Sometimes they are medium. But there are no close-up shots. The films are short. They are about one minute or less. They show tricks, like magic or disappearing acts. The films are like vaudeville shows. They are not like regular movies. A single shot in the viewer’s eyes can be made from many small shots. One film, The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots, shows this. It looks like one shot, but it uses many joined shots.

John Taylor from Caroline supported the Republican Party early. He worked as an agriculturalist and politician. These jobs made him strong in his beliefs about freedom and government. He thought agriculture was the most important job. This made him argue about government, laws, and the court system. He believed the United States could make a perfect government because there was no old tradition to stop it. He believed humans have natural rights that should not be controlled by the government. He thought people with strength and bad ideas could make a better society. But he believed in a government that understands good and evil. He thought a good government protects property and supports agriculture. He wanted a limited federal government. He thought a simple interpretation of the Constitution could be bad. He thought the Declaration of Independence was the true law of the United States.

The number of commuter log submissions fell quickly in the third month of the project. This was a little surprising. It may have been because of the cold weather in New England, or the end of the fall semester. Many people were busy with schoolwork and taking a break for the holidays. The project also had a drop in February. Maybe people felt less excited after a while. To fix this, we had a special challenge week in March. We gave out many prizes, such as gift certificates for local stores. Some people might have come more if we offered a car or bike. If the prizes were bigger over time, more people might have joined. The prizes were good at first, but bigger prizes might have helped in the end.

An ETF, or exchange-traded fund, is like a security that follows an index, a commodity, or a group of assets. It is more flexible than an index fund and trades like a stock on an exchange. An ETF has the benefits of an index fund, like many stocks, and the ability to sell short, buy on margin, and buy just one share. ETFs often have lower costs than mutual funds. However, ETFs need a commission for trades, just like regular stocks. Many types of ETFs are available. It is good for investors to check if stated benefits, like diversification, are true and how much they help.

We will look at the ETF IHF and compare it with its top 10 holdings, which make up 63.58% of the ETF. We will see if owning just the top 10 gives benefits close to owning all stocks in the ETF, and if changing stock choices might give better results. We will use the percentage of assets and current returns to calculate Beta and return for the top 10 holdings.

The top 10 holdings should also have their risk, or standard deviation, checked. This will show if the portfolios are different.

Edgar Allan Poe's "Dream-Land" is a good poem. In this poem, Poe uses the word "Thulé" twice. This word comes from Virgil, a famous writer. In Virgil's writing, Thulé is an island north of Britain. More likely, Poe got this word from a German writer named Goethe. Arthur Quiller-Couch's "Oxford Companion to English Literature" says Goethe wrote a poem called "The King of Thule". This poem is part of the play "Faust". In "The King of Thule", a king loses his wife and becomes sad. He drinks and thinks about his dead wife. He then throws a goblet into the ocean and dies. Poe's "Dream-Land" is similar to "The King of Thule". In "Dream-Land", the speaker feels sad and sees a dark, lonely world. He is like the king in "The King of Thule". Poe uses "ultma Thule" in another poem, "The Pit and the Pendulum". He also uses this word in "Dream-Land" at the start and end. These two poems can be read together. Poe likely knew Goethe because he admired another writer, Tennyson. Poe said he liked Tennyson's work. Also, many people copied and shared Goethe's work.

A judge will likely not dismiss Jennifer Palmer's claim for punitive damages. She must show the store manager, Paul Martin, acted with a willful disregard for the probable harm. She can argue Martin knew about previous similar incidents and still did not clean the spill. Martin’s actions were not fully despicable, but they were reasonable given the facts. On October 13, 2009, employees told Martin about the spill, but he was on dinner break and did not clean it. At 5:30 pm, Palmer slipped and fell, injuring her back. Before this, five slip-and-fall incidents had occurred. In California, a plaintiff can get punitive damages if the defendant acted with oppression, fraud, or malice. Martin's conduct was malicious because he knew the spill could cause harm and did not clean it.

Four years ago, I took a course about Islam at CBC. We talked about if Islam is a hostile religion. This question is still important today. After 9/11, I saw the way people in the media talked about Islam change. They went from being hostile to being very tolerant. Today, we have a president with a Muslim background, which we couldn’t imagine in 2001.

The book about the Prophet Muhammad’s life is interesting. It shows Muhammad in a different way than I thought. I thought he forced people to join Islam. But the book says he was a humble man who people came to know. This makes it seem like Muhammad’s life is being used to make him seem like Jesus. This is wrong because it takes away from Jesus’ life.

There are many stories in the book that seem like they are trying to prove that people converted to Islam on their own. But the stories are often told by other people. This makes them seem less true. I don’t like this because it makes the stories less believable.

What bothers me most is how the book makes Muhammad seem like a perfect, gentle man. But history says he was not like this. If Muslims know this, they might think differently about their religion.

Jesus taught many things during his life. After he died, many people added to these teachings. Over time, Christianity changed. Today, people in the world know more and some think new things. Some people resist new ideas. But, in the future, many Christians will want to know the original teachings. They will want to remove the extra teachings that were added to Christianity. This will take time, maybe many years. When this happens, Christianity will be like it was when Jesus first taught it. People will follow Jesus' ideas. The church will be strong. But, because of this change, there will be more similar beliefs and practices. In the past, there were big changes. For example, the Romans became Christians. Now, there will be another big change. People will look for the original teachings. They will read Jesus' words as stories, not as facts. What happened to Christianity after Jesus' life?
       Jesus lived a long time ago. Before him, there was only Judaism. This was the start of Christianity. The Romans ruled Jerusalem 63 years before Jesus' time. They ruled over the Jewish people. The Jews were not all the same. They split into groups like the Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, and Zealots.

I think The Jungle shows how people are naturally selfish and only care about themselves. They want to make their lives good, not help others. The book shows this in many ways. The main example is the owners and managers of big factories. They only want their companies and factories to be big and strong. They don't care about people or animals hurt by their actions. Upton Sinclair's words show this: "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." He shows the damage from pollution. The owners don't care about the smoke from the factories or the animal waste and urine from the pens around Packingtown.

The owners and managers also don't care about their workers. They want to make or save money, even if it hurts their workers. "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar." They make workers work hard in bad conditions. There were few laws or regulations to protect workers' safety or well-being in that time. The managers and owners could do whatever they wanted. Workers had no help or information. Unions were formed, but they often made money off the workers. Workers were so badly treated, they were called slaves: "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

Many authors use different ways to make readers feel or think about important things. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses many techniques in his novel The Great Gatsby. He pairs words that usually do not fit together to create a feeling. He also gives special meanings to symbols and uses them to make readers think about important things. Fitzgerald builds special meanings for colors, like white/gray and red/pink. He uses these meanings to remind readers of feelings about important things.

Fitzgerald makes white/gray mean uniformity. White is nicer and higher class, while gray is older and faded. He shows this in the beginning of the novel. Daisy and Jordan are always in white. Nick wears white flannels to Gatsby’s party. Everyone wears white, except when Nick sees Gatsby’s party halls, which are colorful.

Fitzgerald also shows gray in unimportant things. Gray cars and gray land are in the valley of ashes. The dog-seller is a gray old man. The Italian child on the train is gray. After building up this meaning, Fitzgerald uses white/gray to show unimportance.

Fitzgerald shows Daisy in white to make her feel less important. Readers think of her as just something Gatsby wants. He does this again with Daisy’s gray collar and her white dress. He shows Daisy as a uniform thing that Gatsby wants.

San Diego is good for farming because it is sunny and mild. Common crops include tomatoes, citrus, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits, berries, honey, and peppers. There is a big market for organic food. Many local organizations have long waiting lists for organic eggs and milk. Many organic farms offer tours and recreational activities.

Organic farming has more costs than regular farming. It needs more labor and management to remove pests and weeds without chemicals. Losses are often bigger. But it has more biodiversity in plants and wildlife.

The land is 160 acres. It is near town and has chaparral, nonnative grassland, and oak woodlands. Many animals and plants live there. Some are endangered, like the Stephens' kangaroo rat and the mountain yellow-legged frog.

Native Americans lived there for a long time. Later, it was used for grazing and wood production. The landowner may need help to make money and keep the land friendly for animals.

I looked at government programs to see how a small farmer could get help. I also found an organic farm in the same area as a model.

Culture helps in negotiation. Culture is not the same everywhere. It is not all the same thing. It is not always easy to understand. Saying things like "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are kind" is too simple. A negotiator needs to know what a culture means and how it affects talks. When meeting a foreign culture, people think of their own culture. Comparisons happen. To understand a foreign culture, one might study its history or learn about its beliefs. It is not good to judge or try to change a culture. Accept it and work with it, especially in negotiations. A negotiator might be in a weak position, so respecting traditions helps. Culture is not just about nations. Companies also have their own cultures. They might have different rules for work or how they treat employees. Some companies let employees help charities, others only with approved ones. Companies in one country can be very different from each other. A negotiator needs to know the values of a culture. If a culture values saving face, a negotiator will not say bad things about his company. The negotiator should also learn about his opponent on a personal level to make the negotiation better.

"The Bible says, 'There is no God,'" said the fool. This phrase is found in Psalm 14 and also in St. Anselm's argument about God's existence. St. Thomas Aquinas also believes that God exists. Both argue for the same God, so we must assume they are both right to compare their arguments. We'll look at each argument. St. Anselm thinks God is inside our minds. We know God exists because He is in our thoughts. We don't need proof from outside. This is what Christians call faith. St. Thomas Aquinas, however, says we can prove God's existence with logic and evidence. He gives five reasons: change, cause, chance, degrees of good, and harmony. Each shows that God's existence is necessary.

A long time ago, a prince named Buddha was born. He left his kingdom and became wise. His teachings started Buddhism. The most important type of Buddhism is Theravada Buddhism. This religion is very old—about 2,500 years. It looks different now than when Buddha was alive. For example, in the Theravada country of Sri Lanka, people do a water-cutting ceremony every year. Both monks and regular people take part in this ceremony. Buddha never taught about this festival. These changes happen from the outside and inside of the Buddhist community. Sometimes, changes are good. Sometimes, they are not.

There are some important words in this story. Internal and external forces are important words. Internal forces are from people who follow Buddha's teachings, like monks and regular people. External forces are from people who do not follow Buddha's teachings. Hostile forces are from people who do not like Buddhism. Benign forces are from people who do not mean to help or harm Buddhism.

Let's look at the basic ideas of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists take refuge in three things: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is made of three books: the Sutta Pitaka, the Vinaya Pitaka, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka. The Sutta Pitaka has teachings from Buddha. The Vinaya Pitaka has rules for monks and regular people to follow. The Abhidhamma Pitaka talks about the world and how it works. Understanding these ideas can help people stop the cycle of life, death, and rebirth. When people understand these ideas, they stop wanting things and stop hating and confusing. They become wise.

The most important idea in Buddhism is the four noble truths. First, life is suffering. Second, wanting things causes suffering. Third, suffering can be stopped. The Vinaya Pitaka has rules for life. Regular people have five rules to follow: do not kill, do not lie, do not steal, do not be sexual, and do not use alcohol. Monks have many more rules to follow. The most important idea in Buddhism is the four noble truths. The first truth is that life is suffering. The second truth is that wanting things causes suffering. The third truth is that suffering can be stopped.

The United States and Mexico had a long fight for 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. The big fight was the Mexican-American War in 1846-1848. The United States won and got Texas and the Southwest as new land. Many other fights happened, but they stopped before World War I. The fight started with problems about religion, culture, and land.
There are many other countries with long fights with their neighbors. The United States and Mexico are like these. In Mexico and Cuba, the United States has long problems. Other countries in Latin America have good relations with the United States.
The United States and Mexico did not like each other's religion. The United States did not like Catholicism and Mexico did not like Protestantism. This was like the Cold War, but it was about religion, not politics. The fight started from the time when the United States was ruled by English and Mexico by Spanish. They did not trust each other.
Diehl and Goerts wrote about 17 fights between Mexico and the United States. Most fights were about land and border problems. Bandits from Mexico made many problems. The fights stopped when Mexico became dependent on the United States and when the United States wanted to help Mexico's economy instead of getting more land.

I became ill suddenly and unexpectedly 15 years ago. I was a nurse. I chose this job because I needed safety and security, which I did not have as a child. People told me, "You can always find work. People always get sick." So, I became a nurse, even though my dream was to be a scientist or journalist.

Now, I am 46, single, and disabled. I cannot work. I live on Social Security Disability, and I have no money. Every day is hard. I could not be here today without my family and good friends. When problems happen, people need help.

We need to help each other in the U.S. We cannot rely on big government alone. It is not good. We should learn to trust each other and ask for help. Preparing for emergencies is good. I have a disaster kit and food supplies. But we must also know our neighbors.

The pioneers who crossed the Rockies did not go alone. They helped each other. So, be prepared and help your neighbors.

Organisms change over time. Why? Are there rules or limits that decide how and why they change? In 1917, D’Arcy Thompson said that scientists can't even dream of defining organic shapes in math. Today, math is used to study how mollusks grow and change. Our study uses math and experiments to find out why Prunum shells change. We use X-ray pictures to find numbers that help us make models of shells. These models help us understand how shells change over time. We use these models with other studies to learn about big changes in this group of creatures.

A shell is like a tube that goes around in 360 degrees. These loops are called whorls. They grow around a line called the columella. The speed of growth can change, and each whorl has a line called a suture. Most shells have the biggest whorl at the end. The spire is the shell's head and the base is the bottom. The animal lives in an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be looked at from different sides, like the top, bottom, front, and back. Usually, a shell is seen from the front with the aperture facing us. To count whorls, look at the top of the shell and find the first suture. Then count the loops. Each loop is about a quarter of a whorl.

Shells can be seen as a series of openings over time. These openings make a path that can be drawn and measured. This path can be shown with math. After making a math formula, we can change some things to see how the mollusk grows.

The number of babies born and die young in Indonesia have not changed much in the last ten years. The country is close to reaching some goals, like clean water and good health. But, the health of children and mothers is not improving enough. We will talk about why this is and what can be done.

In Indonesia, many babies are born with a skilled person helping, 72%. But, this includes workers who cannot do medical things. They cannot help if the baby's mother is having problems. This makes many mothers die, so we still need to work more here.

There are fewer cases of diarrhea in children under five. But, this is not good enough. We do not have enough care after the baby is born. This is also a problem.

Cesarean rates are low, just 4%. This is bad. These rates are higher in towns, 7%, and lower in country areas, 2%. This shows that healthcare is not good in all places. There is also a big difference between poor and rich people. The poor find it harder to get care because of money.

Next, we need to think about how to fix the lack of healthcare. Should we create special programs for health or strengthen the whole system? Special programs can work quickly and have clear goals. But, they can also make other areas get less money and people. Also, too many programs can make things messy and hard to manage.

Victorian novels are known for their detailed description of the aristocracy. Two unusual Victorian novels are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights. Both books use mystery and strange things. This makes characters more interesting. It shows their feelings and reasons.

“Many confusing ideas come to his mind. He seems to be with Sikes and Crackit. They are arguing. He hears their words. Then he sees and hears more. Loud cries and shouts. He is in a dream. He feels pain. He cannot control the events. He cannot even try to save himself. It is like he is not in control of his life. He feels broken.”

“The day seems long and short. It is dark. It is long because of the silence. It is short because it passes quickly.”

Two years ago, I helped Elementary students after school. I was good at English and reading. A teacher asked me to help Adrian, a boy in grade three or four. He had trouble with reading. It was strange. He knew how to say some letters, but not others. He spoke English well, but didn't know the alphabet. His mother spoke only Spanish. I learned some Spanish and we talked. I realized Adrian could read, but didn't know the English alphabet. I hope he's better now.

I tell this story to show the language problem in schools, especially in California. Even a child who speaks English can have reading problems. The solution is not simple. Adrian needed tutoring in reading and the alphabet. Many children need more help. We need to combine different ways to help. The dual language system is good for all children. It helps children who speak Spanish and others too. Some people think it's a waste of resources. But it can help all children. We don't need all teachers to be bilingual. We can have special helpers who speak two languages.

When we are children, many of us learn about something bigger than ourselves. Some go to churches or temples. Others look inside themselves. Some accept what their parents believe. Others do not. Whatever we choose, we try to find our own way to understand what is spiritual.

“What is your favorite bird?” I asked my father. We sat on the porch. Rain fell. We smoked. He looked out, remembering. He was thin. His hair was less now. I felt alone. I did not talk about how I would miss him. I hugged him. I moved my chair near. We watched the rain.

My father died in December. He was sick. His body was weak. He could not get better. I did not want to see him die. So I did not. I remembered him as he lived, not as he died. I lay in bed for three days. No one called me.

The "Gothic Novel" is like an "old-new" mixture, as Ian Watt says in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. People have praised and criticized this type of novel. Some thought it had no real depth, but others loved the "terrible sublime" feeling it gave. The first "Gothic Novel," The Castle of Otranto by Horace Walpole, combined old and new ideas. He used old theater and nature mimicry in modern novels. Walpole called it "A Gothic Story" (4). Gothic novels often use old ideas from medieval theater, architecture, and traditions. When Walpole wrote The Castle of Otranto, the word "gothic" meant old or unsophisticated. The mix of old and new made Gothic novels last long and feel both new and old to readers.

Supply chain management is the process of moving goods from the customer order through raw materials, production, and distribution to the customer. Six key elements are needed: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Managers use these elements to provide good service to customers.

Production is the first step. It is the start of the supply chain. Managers must know what customers want. They look at the market to find out what customers need. After understanding the market, managers decide what products to make and how many to make. They also decide where to make the products. After deciding the location, managers plan workloads and maintain equipment. Every detail in production is important. If details are not planned well, it can cost a company time and money in the long run.

Supply is the second key element. It is about making good choices to decide the best facility and outsourcing partners. A company may have many divisions to make one product. Each division has different equipment, workers, and specialties. Managers decide which division is best for different parts of the product. They may also choose to send some work to other companies. This helps to make products quickly and cheaply.

Hitler, alive in Burma. Cardboard sign says so. Ellen Page, star of Juno, holds sign. Burma, also Myanmar, ruled by bad leaders. They took power in 1962. In 2007, many monks protested. Government let them protest at first. Then, violence started. Many monks and journalists were hurt or killed. Some say more people died than reported. This is not new. Long ago, leaders did this. Early Roman and Japanese leaders thought they were gods. Current leader talks to bad people, like Ted Haggard. Many people died at Tiananmen Square in 1989. Rwanda had a big killing in the 1990s. Hitler's Reich killed many Jews.

Duke Ellington's success in jazz comes from his long career and ability to lead his orchestra. Ellington played piano, but he was a great composer. He wrote songs that show the skills of his band members. He gave soloists space to play freely. He also wrote songs with tight parts that showed the band's style. Ellington knew how to use the sound of each player and how they worked together. This helped him write great jazz songs.

The Grove Music dictionary talks about Ellington's sound and his innovation. They mention "Creole Love Call" as an example. This song uses voice as a musical instrument. Ellington used voice to add color without lyrics. This song has six parts:

First part: Voice and reeds play a call and response. The voice starts smooth and then gets rough.

Second part: Muted trumpet plays alone and uses blue notes.

Third part: Clarinet plays high notes.

Fourth part: The band repeats the first part with brass and reeds.

Fifth part: This is the most exciting part. Reeds play high and use syncopated time.

Sixth part: The song goes back to the first part. The voice uses a "growl" sound.

Ellington's use of voice to add tone is a important part of his style.

In "Hot and Bothered," Ellington shows his skill with tight orchestra and tone color. He uses "Bubber" Miley's trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing to make a rich sound. In "It Don't Mean a Thing," Ellington uses Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton's muted trombone to play the melody.

She always needed something, but nothing made her happy. This feeling started when she was 14. It is still here at 17. She wants a person, not a thing. But no boy interested her. She thought about this often, but no good ideas came. She lived with this question.

At home, she was calm. Her parents were good and kind. They argued rarely. Her personality was different, so they argued about her independence. She was their good daughter.

Today was not calm. She heard her mother scream. She ran to help. Her mother was hurt. She needed to go to the hospital. Her daughter helped her. She drove her mother in the car. They went to the hospital.

The hospital was not a good place. It smelled bad. But she was only thinking about helping her mother. She called for help. Doctors looked at her mother. She waited, worried.

Her mother fell from a step stool while trying to get a vase.

This study shows that eating the Mediterranean Diet (Med Diet), as shown by a high score on the alternate Mediterranean diet (aMed score), lowers the risk of heart disease and stroke. The aMed diet is like the Med diet but with more plant foods, like fruits, nuts, and whole grains, and less animal products. Moderate alcohol is allowed.

Past studies found that the Med diet lowers the risk of heart disease and stroke. An experiment showed that the Med diet helps with weight loss. This study also looks at stroke and stroke deaths.

This study follows 74,886 women, 38 to 63 years old, without heart disease or diabetes. The Nurses' Health Study has 121,700 female nurses in 11 US states. Six times, from 1984 to 2004, they calculated the aMed score from a food survey. Most nurses stayed in the study for 20 years. The survey was checked for accuracy. Reports of heart disease and stroke were confirmed by medical records.

Body weight, smoking, aspirin use, vitamins, menopause status, and physical activity were calculated. Cumulative averages of the aMed score were made to show long-term diet. Adjustments were made for factors that could confuse the results.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to study the link between the aMed score and heart disease and stroke. During 20 years, 2391 cases of heart disease, 1763 cases of stroke, and 1077 cardiovascular deaths were found. Women with the highest aMed score had less risk of heart disease and stroke than those with the lowest score (relative risk, 0.71).

In 2007, the United States had a big financial problem. Many people lost jobs, and the housing market crashed. Big companies lost money. This problem is still happening today. We need to know how this happened and how to stop it. The problem started because bankers and companies gave bad loans. They did this because of bad rules. The government also helped with this. Banks sold bad loans to other companies. When people could not pay, the banks lost money. This made the whole economy bad.

The problem started in 1999 during Clinton's time. The president wanted to stay in power, so he changed rules to help people buy houses. He thought this would make him popular. Steven Holmes of the New York Times said this could cause big problems. He said, "Fannie Mae... could have trouble in a bad economy." He was right. The bad loans led to the big financial crash.

Many things caused the economy to crash. One was the way mortgages were set up. Some mortgages could change with prices. This made the economy very weak. When the housing bubble burst, banks lost a lot of money. The top five banks had $4.1 trillion in mortgage debts, which was 30% of the USA's GDP. Bear Stearns and Merrill Lynch were sold cheaply. Lehman Brothers was closed, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley became banks with rules. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt and were taken over by the government in 2008.

Exposition. This is where you begin your story. It is either exciting or boring, depending on how you write. Dr. Merlin sometimes shouts at her computer when she reads too much information. It is not good.

You already know the writing tip, "Show, don't tell." But Dr. Merlin still writes long passages where nothing happens. Exposition is like a little devil that says to quickly tell your story instead of showing it.

In stories, exposition is when one character tells another about something important. In movies, this is when a character tells another character a lot of information. In books, the author does this.

For example, you read a story where the heroine meets her husband, they marry, and then he dies. You do not want to read two pages about this with little dialogue. You want the author to show you the husband's character, how he loves his wife, and how his presence changed her.

The author should spend time on the husband's character so you care about him and his death. You should understand the heroine's thoughts and feelings through his eyes.

In short, you need to show, not just tell, the story.

Sometimes it is easy to rush past things. You might want to quickly tell about a new character. He was in the Air Force, now works at a gas station, married twice, no kids, likes fishing, dreams of owning the gas station, and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast. But you should show these things with dialogue and actions.

I watched two news shows from Columbus, Ohio. One was live on NBC 4. It was about a man who stabbed his wife in Ashley, Ohio. The news showed his picture and said he looked bad. They talked about this story for two minutes. The news said he stabbed her many times and was arrested.

The second story was about a young man named Travis Buyers. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area. He was critically hurt, but no one was arrested. The police were investigating. This story was short. I think this was because he was a black man. I have seen this happen before. If a white person is hurt, the news talks a lot about it. But if a minority person is hurt, the news talks less.

The next story was about a bullet hole in a helicopter. The news said it was a .22 caliber bullet. They said it was from a rifle. They offered a five-thousand dollar reward for information about the shooter.

The next story was about rain and thunderstorms coming on Saturday. They said the temperature would be between 80 and 85 degrees. This story was short, but they wanted people to stay tuned.

The next story was about a robbery at a store on Clime Road. A dark-skinned black man robbed the store. He was about six feet tall and weighed 150 pounds. The news talked a lot about his skin color.

The last story was about a man named Rene Rodriguez. He was a drug kingpin. He was sentenced to 300 months in prison for selling drugs. The news said he was Hispanic, but I don't think that was important to the story.

Brothers have a close bond. This bond is strong and cannot be broken. Many feelings are part of this bond, like love, pride, and jealousy. Brothers understand each other more than anyone else. They see themselves in their brother. In hard times, this bond shows its true nature, whether good or bad. The feelings come with a cost. Understanding these feelings helps deal with their effects. When a brother looks at another brother, they see their own reflection. They see themselves as they truly are, not how others see them. They see their own actions and the results of those actions. In "The Scarlet Ibis", two brothers explore this theme. They go on a journey, but one does not return. The theme is shown through the main character, Doodle, and his feelings.

The main character feels proud. From their first trip to their last, he is angry with Doodle. He wanted a brother to teach and play with. But Doodle has a weak heart. He cannot run or climb like the main character. This is hard for the main character. He even thinks about killing Doodle. But when Doodle smiles at him, the main character feels hope. This shows his love for Doodle is strong.

The brain is a complex system. As technology changed, the ways we talk about the brain also changed. We used to say the brain is like a wax tablet, then a sheet of papyrus, then a book, and now a computer. Remember, these comparisons can be wrong.

Information processing starts with sensors. These turn physical things like touch, heat, sound, or light into electrical signals. The brain changes these signals over and over again. There are two ways it does this: bottom-up and top-down. Bottom-up processing uses simple things like color, shape, and where things change to understand what we see. Top-down processing helps us know what we are looking at faster.

The brain decides what information is important and what we should pay attention to. For example, when you look at your shoes, you do not see each blade of grass. But you can hear your name in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and attention changes how we see things.

The brain must store information. There are different types of memory: sensory, working, and long-term. Sensory memory turns information into signals. Working memory stores information for a short time. Long-term memory stores information in proteins.

There are many ways to think about how the brain stores knowledge. Some ways are based on how we remember things, computer science, or how the brain works. The semantic network model says that knowledge is like a network of ideas. Each idea is a node, and nodes are linked by how related they are. For example, the idea of a "chair" is linked to "table," which is linked to "wooden."

Aldous Huxley criticizes the upcoming threat of technology and capitalism in Brave New World. In this novel, people value community more than themselves. They are conditioned to pursue happiness from a young age. The citizens are pawns, following rules set by the World Controller. The book shows how these systems can cause problems. It uses ideas from Marxism to show these problems. For example, people may not know how the economy works. This is called false consciousness. The common people are not aware of the true relations between social classes. They are more interested in money and goods. This is controlled by the World Controller. The lower classes are unaware of this manipulation. They just want to consume and enjoy life. The upper classes know about this but do not do anything. Relationships between people are not deep. They do not show true emotions. Instead, people just talk about physical appearance. This shows how technology and capitalism can make people unfree and expressionless. Love and strong emotions do not exist. People are just happy to fit into their society. They are content with their place in the hierarchy. This shows how capitalism can make people happy to be part of a system that keeps them in their place.

I have been a student at University Park for two and a half years, or four and a half semesters. It is hard to get around campus. My first year, I lived in East Halls dorm, far from most classes. Walking from Stuart Hall to Willard building could take 25 minutes, especially in bad weather. Now, that empty space is filled with sports fields, new buildings, and apartments. As campus grows, it's harder to travel around. The best solution is a bicycle, but we need to build campus with bicyclists in mind.

I talked to a friend who rode a bike again after years. He said, "Bikes are great. They are the best way to get around." Bicycling is good for health and fast travel. Walking takes too much time. I live off campus, far from the center. My smartest choice this year was to buy a bike. It takes 5 minutes to ride to Thomas building, compared to 25 minutes by walk. However, Pollock Road is not always easy. If I didn't have a bike, walking would be my only option. Walking to Thomas would take extra 30-40 minutes each day, over two and a half hours a week. That's too much time.

In pursuing an education in social work, I intend to follow a career path with the Division of Family and Children Services to help children who have been abused or neglected; and to provide support for troubled families. Values that I can provide to the social work field include the following: service, respect, ethical nature, commitment to help improve relationships between others and to improve myself professionally to remain competent in my field. These core values are not just important to social workers; they are important to me personally. 

	I have always wanted to help others, but I was unsure of the career path that I wanted to follow. Throughout my years in high school and college, I saw many individuals flee from their problems in denial and a few used coping mechanisms that were less than ideal. Because of situations that I have witnessed, I chose to pursue a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. Still unsure of a career path, I decided to take a break once I graduated from Piedmont College in 2009. One day that summer, I visited a friend who introduced me to a sixteen year-old boy sitting nervously on her couch. She explained to me why he was visiting: to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I learned that he had called the police to his parent’s residence. To see if I could help in any way, I drove over to his parents’ house. Once there, I privately explained my concerns to the police and told them I had just graduated with a degree in Psychology from Piedmont College. The police requested that I talk to the parents since there was nothing that the law could do for the teenager. When I questioned the parents about the situation, they seemed nervous and used excuses to describe their son’s “manipulative” behavior for involving outside sources to resolve “simple” disputes. After this particular experience, I began to seriously consider a career in social work to help children with “simple” disputes among family members.

	Another value that is important for the field of social work is social justice. As a society, we claim that the individual is important and we mourn those that we have lost. The concept of the “individual” that society holds is more a follower of archaic traditions than actual uniqueness. So, if society mourns lost individuals, then why do we strive to be similar to “everyone else?” I am an individual and do not enjoy placing limitations on myself to be similar to others. Throughout my years at high school and college, I protested against social injustice whenever I could: coloring my hair unnatural colors, wearing clothing that fit my personality, piercing my ears past the traditional set, declaring my involvement with GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), fighting against both racism and discrimination whenever I witnessed it, etc. I believe in social justice and I will continue to protest against social injustice.

The following paper addresses the Biological and Sociocultural models in relation to the disorder insomnia. The biological model focuses on genetic information that is inherited as well as medical aspects of health. The Sociocultural models look at environmental relationships and their applications to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. The following review of insomnia looks at these models and explains each piece of research chosen to relate to and to better explain the models. The explanations of the research and their findings are then critiqued to mention their specific strengths and weaknesses.

A sleep disorder can be characterized as a primary sleep disorder, a sleep disorder related to another mental disorder, or a sleep disorder related to other issues. The Primary sleep disorders are Dyssonmias or Parasomnias while sleep disorders related to another mental disorder are related to an Axis I or Axis II disorder. Other categories of sleep disorders can be due to medical complications or the intake of a substance. The Dyssomnias are: Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing- Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). While Primary Insomnia is a complication in adequate or maintained sleep, Primary Hypersomnia is a difficulty in staying awake, both for at least a one month period of time. Narcolepsy involves cataplexy and/ or automatic REM. While Dyssonmias focus on initiating and remaining asleep, the Parasomnias are sleep disorders associated with behavioral abnormalities and/ or physiological occurrences. Parasomnias are Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. The sleep disorders related to another mental disorder involve sleep difficulties due to Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Mental Retardation). The following review focuses on insomnia, and somewhat on primary sleep disorders in general in relation to the biological and sociocultural models.

	 The biological model of sleep disorders focuses on genes, heritable factors, and physiologically acquired aspect of sleep disorders. Neurons in the hypothalamus containing orexin are responsible for the regulation of sleep and wakefulness. This study experimented with mice and found that there are phenotypic GABAB receptors on the orexin neurons which are specifically responsible for sleep/ wake states. The activation of the GABAA receptor induces responses that promote sleep. If it is inhibited from firing, this can cause reduced anxiety and induce sleep. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) increased sleep time (Matsuki et al., 2009). Such results imply that the animal models of mice can be generalized to studies in humans.
